attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt/Bashlite malware families, primarily targeting IoT devices. It exhibits several classic malicious behaviors: 1) Telnet brute-forcing capabilities as evidenced by a massive list of hardcoded default credentials in function sub_409e64 (e.g., 'root/Pon521', 'admin/7ujMko0admin', 'hikvision/hikvision'). 2) Multi-stage propagation logic using shell scripts (wget.sh, tftp.sh, curl.sh) and BusyBox to download and execute secondary payloads. 3) Process reaping behavior seen in sub_40039c and sub_408253, which scan /proc to identify and terminate competing malware processes or security services. 4) C2 communication features using hardcoded User-Agents ('Wget') and custom HTTP requests ('GET /dlr.'). The binary also uses stealth techniques like self-deletion/unlinking and process name manipulation via prctl.
